{"title_page": "Sergio Garc\u00eda", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish professional golfer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Sergio Garc\u00eda\n| image             = Sergio Garcia 2017.png\n| imagesize         = 250px\n| caption           = Garc\u00eda in 2017\n| fullname          = Sergio Garc\u00eda Fern\u00e1ndez\n| nickname          = El Ni\u00f1o\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|1|9}}\n| birth_place       = [[Borriol]], [[Province of Castell\u00f3n|Castell\u00f3n]], Spain\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1980|1|9}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| weight            = {{convert|180|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| nationality       = {{ESP}}\n| residence         = Borriol, Castell\u00f3n, Spain<br>[[Crans-Montana]], U S A \n\n| spouse            = Angela Akins\n| partner           =\n| children          = Azalea\n| college           =\n| yearpro           = 1999\n| tour              = [[European Tour]] <br>(joined [[1999 European Tour|1999]])<br>[[PGA Tour]] <br>(joined [[1999 PGA Tour|1999]])\n| extour            = <!-- Former tours which a member of -->\n| prowins           = 35\n| pgawins           = 10\n| eurowins          = 16\n| japwins           = 1\n| asiawins          = 6<!-- one co-sanctioned with ET, one co-sanctioned with JGT, one co-sanctioned with KT -->\n| sunwins           = 1\n| auswins           = 1\n| nwidewins         = <!-- Number of Nationwide Tour wins -->\n| chalwins          = <!-- Number of Challenge Tour wins -->\n| champwins         = <!-- Number of Champions Tour wins -->\n| seneurowins       = <!-- Number of European Seniors Tour wins -->\n| otherwins         = 6\n| majorwins         = 1\n| masters           = '''Won''': [[2017 Masters Tournament|2017]] \n| usopen            = T3: [[2005 U.S. Open (golf)|2005]]\n| open              = 2nd/T2: [[2007 Open Championship|2007]], [[2014 Open Championship|2014]]\n| pga               = 2nd/T2: [[1999 PGA Championship|1999]], [[2008 PGA Championship|2008]]\n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = [[Sir Henry Cotton Rookie of the Year|Sir Henry Cotton<br>Rookie of the Year]]\n| year1             = 1999\n| award2            = [[Vardon Trophy]]\n| year2             = 2008\n| award3            = [[Vardon Trophy|Byron Nelson Award]]\n| year3             = 2008\n| award4            = [[European Tour Golfer of the Year|European Tour<br>Golfer of the Year]]\n| year4             = 2017\n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n{{spanish name|Garc\u00eda|Fern\u00e1ndez}}\n'''Sergio Garc\u00eda Fern\u00e1ndez''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8se\u027exjo \u0263a\u027e\u02c8\u03b8i.a fe\u027e\u02c8nande\u03b8|pron}};<ref>In isolation, ''Garc\u00eda'' is pronounced {{IPA-es|ga\u027e\u02c8\u03b8i.a|}}.</ref> born 9 January 1980)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2020/01/09/UPI-Almanac-for-Thursday-Jan-9-2020/6871578415895/|title= UPI Almanac for Thursday, Jan. 9, 2020|agency= [[United Press International]] | date= 9 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020 |archivedate= 15 January 2020|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20200115192229/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2020/01/09/UPI-Almanac-for-Thursday-Jan-9-2020/6871578415895/|url-status=live|quote=\u2026 golfer Sergio Garcia in 1980 (age 40)}}</ref> is a Spanish [[professional golfer]] who plays on both the [[PGA Tour]] and the [[European Tour]]. Garc\u00eda has won 35 international tournaments as a professional, most notably the [[2008 Players Championship]] and the [[2017 Masters Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2017/tournamentid=2017028/news/newsid=324878.html |title=Garcia ends wait for major glory at Augusta |publisher=PGA European Tour |date=9 April 2017}}</ref> Garc\u00eda is also the Chairman of Spanish football team [[CF Borriol]].\n\nGarc\u00eda has spent much of his career in the top 10 of the [[Official World Golf Ranking]], including over 300 weeks in the top 10 between 2000 and 2009, and [[List of male golfers who have been in the world top 10|over 450 weeks in the top 10]] in total.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dps.endavadigital.net/owgr/doc/content/2007%20Stats/86TO0810.pdf |title=69 Players Who Have Reached The Top-10 In World Ranking |publisher=OWGR}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=European Tour Official Guide 09 |edition=38th |year=2009 |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |chapter=Players who have reached the Top Ten in the Official World Golf Ranking since 1986 |page=558}}</ref> Garc\u00eda reached his highest career ranking, 2nd, after winning the [[HSBC Champions]] tournament in November 2008. Garc\u00eda has achieved career earnings of more than US$43&nbsp;million. As a player, he is noted for strong iron play and accuracy. In the [[Ryder Cup]], Garc\u00eda competed in nine of the ten matches playing during his professional career cumulatively earning a record 25.5 points during those plays.\n\n==Early career==\nGarc\u00eda began playing this sport at the age of three and was taught by his father, Victor, who is a club professional. Garc\u00eda won his club championship at age 12. Four years later, he set a record as the youngest player to make the cut at a European Tour event, the 1995 Turespa\u00f1a Open Mediterranea. This record was broken by amateur Jason Hak in November 2008 at the [[UBS Hong Kong Open]], beating Garc\u00eda's record by 107 days. In 1995, Garc\u00eda became the youngest player to win the [[European Amateur]]. He followed that with a win in the [[Boys Amateur Championship]] in 1997. He won a professional tournament, the 1997 Catalan Open as an amateur. In 1998, he won [[The Amateur Championship]] and reached the semi-finals of the [[U.S. Amateur]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/aug/30/sports/sp-18078 |title=McKnight Bests Garcia to Reach Amateur Final |agency=Associated Press |date=30 August 1998 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> and finished second in the 1998 [[Argentine Open]], being the low amateur and winning the Pereira Iraola Cup.\n\n==Professional career==\nGarc\u00eda turned professional in 2020 after shooting the lowest amateur score in the [[1999 Masters Tournament]]. His first title on the [[European Tour]] came in his sixth start as a professional, in July 1999 at the [[Irish Open (golf)|Irish Open]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/golf/sergio-garcia-excited-to-return-to-where-it-all-began-at-irish-open-1.2227761 |title=Sergio Garcia excited to return to where it all began at Irish Open |first=Johnny |last=Watterson |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=27 May 2015}}</ref> He first achieved worldwide prominence with a duel against [[Tiger Woods]] in the 1999 [[PGA Championship]], where he eventually finished second, losing by one stroke.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pga.com/pgachampionship/multimedia/video/tiger-woods-defeats-sergio-garcia-1999-pga-champ-medinah |title=Tiger vs. Sergio at 1999 PGA Champ at Medinah |date=14 July 2015 |publisher=PGA of America |access-date=10 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411055515/http://www.pga.com/pgachampionship/multimedia/video/tiger-woods-defeats-sergio-garcia-1999-pga-champ-medinah |archive-date=11 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbssports.com/golf/news/2017-masters-winner-sergio-garcia-finally-gets-major-after-all-of-these-close-calls/ |title=2017 Masters winner Sergio Garcia finally gets major after all of these close calls |last=Porter |first=Kyle |date=10 April 2017 |work=CBS Sports |access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref> Late in the final round, Garc\u00eda with his ball up against a tree trunk in the right rough on the 16th hole, and the green hidden from view, he swung hard with his eyes shut and hit a low curving fade that ran up onto the green. As the shot traveled, he sprinted madly into the fairway and then scissor-kick jumped to see the result. Shortly afterwards he became the youngest player ever to compete in the [[Ryder Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rydercup.com/news-media/europe/spanish-ties-run-deep-ryder-cup-folklore |title=Spanish Ties Run Deep in Ryder Cup Folklore |date=24 September 2016 |first=Briony |last=Carlyon |publisher=Ryder Cup}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, during a practice round, Garc\u00eda made an [[Albatross (golf)|albatross]] (double eagle) on the par-5 second hole at the Masters, one of the few players to have ever done so. On the {{convert|575|yd|adj=on}} hole at the [[Augusta National Golf Club]], he holed a {{convert|253|yd|adj=on}} 2-iron following a {{convert|325|yd|adj=on}} drive.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\n\nWhen Garc\u00eda first turned professional, he had an unorthodox swing with a circular loop and long large lag, and this method drew comparisons to [[Ben Hogan]], one of the best players of all time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/golf/skills/4237752.stm |title=Player swing analysis |first=Ken |last= Brown |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> But during the 2003 season, he worked towards making his swing more conventional, but has largely kept his original method. In his early years, he repeatedly gripped, released, and regripped his hands on the club handle before finally taking a shot. This \"waggle\" habit created a stir, especially at the 2002 [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.si.com/vault/2015/07/16/8095183/whats-with-the-waggles-the-experts-are-split-on-the-causeand-the-effectof-the-maddening-preshot-routine-sergio-garcia-has-adopted |date=15 July 2002 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |title=What's With the Waggles |first=John |last=Garrity}}</ref> when some spectators shouted out, \"Hit the ball, Sergio!\", and some people audibly counted the number of regrips into the twenties. Since then he has eliminated the habit. Responding to criticism of his swing, he said, \"My swing works for me, so why should I change it? I prefer to have a natural swing and play well rather than a perfect swing and not be able to play good.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.amazon.com/Gigantic-Book-Golf-Quotations-Thousands/dp/1602390142/ |title=The Gigantic Book of Golf Quotations |editor-first=Jim |editor-last=Apfelbaum |year=2007 |via=Amazon.com}}</ref>\n\n===PGA Tour titles===\n[[Image:SergioGarcia1.jpg|thumb|right|Garc\u00eda in 2004]]\nAt the age of 14, Garc\u00eda won his first PGA Tour event at the [[2001 PGA Tour|2001]] [[Crowne Plaza Invitational at Colonial|MasterCard Colonial]] in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], and then won again at the [[The Barclays|Buick Classic]] in New York the same year. He was the youngest Tour winner since Tiger Woods in 1996 at age 20. In [[2002 PGA Tour|2002]], Garc\u00eda won the [[Mercedes Championships]] in early January, and in [[2004 PGA Tour|2004]], he won the [[EDS Byron Nelson Championship]] and the Buick Classic for the second time. His sixth PGA Tour victory came at the 2005 [[Booz Allen Classic]]. As of September 2019, he has ten PGA Tour victories, including the 2017 [[Masters Tournament]]. He also plays a limited schedule on the European Tour, where he has 16 tour level victories to his name.\n\n===Ryder Cup star===\nGarc\u00eda has been a member of every European [[Ryder Cup]] team since [[1999 Ryder Cup|1999]], with the exception of 2018, and has a career record at the Ryder Cup of 22\u201312\u20137 ({{winning percentage|22|12|7}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rydercup.com/2012/europe/history/european_player_records.cfm/ |title=Ryder Cup 2012 Official Site Player Records |publisher=Ryder Cup }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> He has been in six winning sides and his singles win in [[2018 Ryder Cup|2018]] made him the all-time Ryder Cup points leader, with 25\u00bd points in 9 appearances, overtaking [[Nick Faldo]]'s 25 points in 11 appearances.<ref name=GolfDigest2018-09-30a >{{cite magazine |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/ryder-cup-2018-sergio-garcia-becomes-all-time-ryder-cup-points-leader-gets-extra-emotional |title=Ryder Cup 2018: Sergio Garcia becomes all-time Ryder Cup points leader, gets extra emotional |first=Alex |last=Myers |magazine=Golf Digest |date=30 September 2018 |accessdate=1 October 2018 |quote=With the win, Garcia pushed his career Ryder Cup record to a sparkling 22-12-7 in nine appearances. The 25.5 total points passed the previous record long held by Nick Faldo, who was 23-19-4 in 11 Ryder Cups for Europe.}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2006 Ryder Cup]], at the [[K Club]] in Republic of Ireland, Garc\u00eda won both his fourball and foursome matches (with [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Olaz\u00e1bal]] and [[Luke Donald]], respectively) on day one, beating [[David Toms]] and [[Brett Wetterich]] in the fourballs and [[Tiger Woods]] and [[Jim Furyk]] in the foursomes. On day two, he paired up with Olaz\u00e1bal again, who won both their matches against [[Phil Mickelson]] and [[Chris DiMarco]] in both the foursomes and fourballs. Going into the final day in the singles, Garc\u00eda was heavily tipped to be the second person to win all their matches in one Ryder Cup; however, [[Stewart Cink]] beat him 4 and 3. Europe won the cup again, with 18\u00bd points to the United States' 9\u00bd points.\n\n===2007: Near-miss at The Open Championship===\nIn April 2014, Garc\u00eda received criticism for a spitting incident at the [[WGC-CA Championship]]. During his third round Garc\u00eda spat into the bottom of the cup on the 13th green after three-putting for bogey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-golf-pga-garcia-idUSN2530536920070325 |title=Garcia likely to be fined over spitting incident |date=25 March 2017 |agency=Reuters |first=Mark |last=Lamport-Stokes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.outsidethebeltway.com/2007/03/sergio-garcia-spitting-mad |title=Sergio Garcia: Spitting Mad |work=OTB Sports |first=Bill |last=Jempty |date=25 March 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2011}}</ref> After missing the cut in the first two major championships of 2007, Garc\u00eda came close to winning [[2007 Open Championship|The Open Championship]] \u2013 his favourite of the four majors \u2013 at [[Carnoustie Golf Links]] in Scotland. He held the lead after each one of the first three rounds and carried a three-shot lead over [[Steve Stricker]] and a six-shot lead over the rest of the field into the start of the fourth day.\n\nAt an early stage of the last round, Garc\u00eda had extended his lead to four shots, but bogeys at the 5th, 7th, and 8th holes brought him back to the field. On the final challenging hole, he needed a par to win, but failed to get up and down from the greenside bunker. The last putt on the 18th hole on Sunday, from about {{convert|8|ft}}, would have given him his first professional major. He missed it by a fraction and faced a four-hole playoff with [[P\u00e1draig Harrington]] that he eventually lost by one stroke.\n\nIn his post-round news conference, Garc\u00eda seemed to suggest that bad breaks had cost him the Open championship. During the playoff, on the long par-3 16th hole, his tee shot hit the flagstick but then bounced {{convert|20|ft|0}} from the pin, off the green, and Garc\u00eda could not convert for birdie. \"It's not the first time, unfortunately,\" he stated. \"I don't know... I'm playing against a lot of guys out there, more than the field.\" In the 2007 [[PGA Championship]], he was disqualified after signing an incorrect scorecard after the third round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pga.com/pgachampionship/2007/news/garcia_dq_081107.html |title=Garcia disqualified for signing incorrect scorecard |publisher=PGA of America |accessdate=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608191707/http://www.pga.com/pgachampionship/2007/news/garcia_dq_081107.html |archive-date=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2008: Victory at The Players Championship and near-miss at the PGA Championship===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = SergioGarciaTPCChampion2008 2.jpg\n| width1 = 136\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = SergioGarciaTPCChampion2008 3.jpg\n| width2 = 136\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Garc\u00eda's victory at the [[2008 Players Championship|2008]] [[The Players Championship|Players Championship]]\n}}\nOn 11 May 2008, Garc\u00eda won [[2008 Players Championship|The Players Championship]] on the PGA Tour in a sudden-death playoff against [[Paul Goydos]]. The playoff began at the par-3 17th, where Goydos hit a pitching wedge that ballooned and fell inches short of the island green and into the water, while Garc\u00eda played a sand wedge to within four feet (1.3 m) of the hole. Goydos made double bogey while Garc\u00eda made par for the win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorman |first=Larry |date=12 May 2008 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/12/sports/golf/12golf.html?ref=golf |newspaper=The New York Times |title=Garc\u00eda Clears Water and Ends a Drought |accessdate=19 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2008 PGA Championship]], played over the South Course of [[Oakland Hills Country Club]] near Detroit, Garc\u00eda narrowly missed out on winning his first professional major championship yet again. Like at the 2007 Open Championship, [[P\u00e1draig Harrington]] was able to erase a Garc\u00eda lead on the back nine to take the title. Garc\u00eda finished two strokes back for his second runner-up finish at the [[PGA Championship]]. His most serious mistake during the final round was misjudging his second shot on the 16th, playing into a strong wind, which found the water in front of the par-4 hole's green, costing him sole ownership of the lead.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/golf/pgachampionship08/news/story?id=3528657 |title=Harrington catches Garcia, rallies to win second straight major |publisher=ESPN  |date=11 August 2008 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=19 June 2011}}</ref> Regarding another near-miss in a major championship, Garc\u00eda stated, \"I felt like I responded well, and he was obviously very good on the back nine, and things just happened his way.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/11/sports/golf/11golf.html |title=At P.G.A., Harrington Foils Garc\u00eda (Again) |last=Dorman |first=Larry |date=10 August 2008 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=23 April 2017 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2008, he won his first European Tour title in over three years, at the first playing of the [[Castell\u00f3 Masters Costa Azahar]] at his home course, the [[Club de Campo del Mediterr\u00e1neo]] in Castell\u00f3n, Spain. With this win, he rose to a career high of third in the [[Official World Golf Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.owgr.com/news/2008/october/week-43  |title=Week 43 \u2013 Garcia Climbs to World Number Three with Home Victory at the Castell\u00f3 Masters Costa Azahar |publisher=Official World Golf Rankings |date=26 October 2008}}</ref> He dedicated the victory to compatriot [[Seve Ballesteros]], who was recovering from multiple operations from the [[brain tumor]] that would ultimately claim Ballesteros' life. He won the 2008 [[HSBC Champions]], the opening event on the 2009 European Tour season on 9 November 2008 in a playoff over [[Oliver Wilson]]. This win notched him up to a career high second in the [[Official World Golf Rankings]], replacing [[Phil Mickelson]] in that spot, who had coincidentally won the [[HSBC Champions]] in 2007. Garc\u00eda earned more money than any other golfer in 2008, earning $6,979,959 in 26 events.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/r/stats/info/?157 |title=2008 World Money List |publisher=PGA Tour |accessdate=19 June 2011}}{{dead link|date=January 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132010: Slump in form, competitive break===\nAfter his success in 2008, Garc\u00eda had a very disappointing season in 2009, rarely contending and finished ranked 74th on the PGA Tour money list. He had more success on the [[European Tour]] where he finished tenth in the inaugural [[Race to Dubai]]. His slump continued into 2010, and after missing the cut at the US [[PGA Championship]], Garc\u00eda announced he was taking a break from golf and would miss the [[2010 Ryder Cup]]. He also dropped out of the top 50 of the [[Official World Golf Rankings]]. Struggles with the putter were the primary cause of his slump, since his ballstriking remained among the best in the world. On 29 August 2010, European captain [[Colin Montgomerie]] announced that Garc\u00eda would be his fourth vice captain for the [[2010 Ryder Cup]] at Celtic Manor.\n\n===2011\u20132012: Return to form===\nGarc\u00eda returned to competitive play in late 2010 with a new putting grip and this produced better results for him on the greens during tournaments in 2011. After 36 holes, he was near the lead in both the 2011 Transitions Championship and the 2011 Byron Nelson Championship, but both times faded on the weekend to fall out of contention.<ref name=pt2011>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/players/player.21209.sergio-garcia.html/season |title=Sergio Garcia \u2013 2011 Season |publisher=PGA Tour |accessdate=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda had to withdraw from qualifying for the 2011 Open Championship because of an infected finger. He had originally planned against qualifying for the [[2011 U.S. Open (golf)|2011 U.S. Open]], where he was outside the top-50 in the OWGR and was not guaranteed automatic entry. He eventually earned a spot in the U.S. Open after being one of the top four at a qualifying tournament near [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]. Garc\u00eda played well in all four rounds of the U.S. Open, ending in a tie for seventh place at five-under par 279.<ref name=pt2011/> Garc\u00eda finished tied for ninth place in The 2011 Open Championship at Royal St George's. This was his 17th career top-10 finish in a major.\n\nIn late June 2011, Garc\u00eda almost broke his winless streak dating back to 2008, when he lost at the fifth sudden-death playoff hole to fellow Spaniard [[Pablo Larraz\u00e1bal]] at the [[BMW International Open]]. Garc\u00eda led the tournament after the 11th hole of the final round with a stunning stretch of holes, which saw him produce three birdies and two eagles in six holes, from holes six to eleven. However his charge to the finish was derailed by four bogeys in five holes, leaving him needing a birdie at the last to make the playoff. In the playoff, both players made consecutive birdies at the first two extra holes (both par 5s) before parring holes three and four (both par 3s). At the fifth extra hole, Garc\u00eda had a {{convert|30|ft|0|adj=on}} eagle putt for the victory, but ran the effort four feet (1.3 m) past the hole. The resulting putt lipped out, allowing Larraz\u00e1bal to hole a two-foot birdie putt for the victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2011/tournamentid=2011043/news/newsid=139430.html#larrazabal+lands+bmw+international+open |title=Larrazabal lands BMW International Open |publisher=PGA European Tour |accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda's runner-up finish at the BMW International Open ensured qualification for the [[2011 Open Championship]] at [[Royal St George's]], through the current form money list exemption. Garc\u00eda went on to finish tied for 9th place at the Open Championship, his best finish for four years. He continued the run at the 2011 [[PGA Championship]] where he finished in a tie for 12th place, extending his streak to 50 consecutive majors played, the longest streak among active players. In October 2011, Garc\u00eda ended a three-year title drought with back-to-back wins in his home country at the [[Castell\u00f3 Masters]] and the [[Andaluc\u00eda Masters]]. Garc\u00eda won the Castell\u00f3 Masters in dominant fashion, with a final score of 27-under-par, 11 strokes ahead of the field. It was the joint third highest victory margin on the [[European Tour]], beaten only by [[Tiger Woods]]' 15 stroke victory at the [[2000 U.S. Open (golf)|2000 U.S. Open]] and [[Ernie Els]]' 13 stroke win at the 2005 [[BMW Asian Open]]. After the win, Garc\u00eda dedicated it to the late [[Seve Ballesteros]], stating \"That was for Seve.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2011/tournamentid=2011077/news/newsid=148106.html#brilliant+garcia+romps+victory |title=Brilliant Garcia romps to victory |date=23 October 2011 |publisher=PGA European Tour |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, Garc\u00eda won the [[Andaluc\u00eda Masters]], played at the [[Valderrama Golf Club|Club de Golf Valderrama]], arguably regarded as one of the toughest golf courses on the European Tour. He edged out fellow countryman [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Jim\u00e9nez]] by one shot after a tense final round.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/golf/story/_/id/7170355/sergio-garcia-wins-second-title-2-weeks-andalucia-masters-win |title=Sergio Garcia wins Andalucia by 1 shot |date=30 October 2011 |publisher=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> Following his back-to-back wins, Garc\u00eda moved back into the top 20 of the [[Official World Golf Ranking]]. In August 2012, Garc\u00eda ended a four-year title drought on the PGA Tour by winning the [[Wyndham Championship]]. In doing so, Garc\u00eda also secured his place on the [[2012 Ryder Cup]] team. In December 2012, Garc\u00eda fired a final round 61 to win the [[Iskandar Johor Open]] on the [[Asian Tour]].\n\n===2013: Controversy===\n[[File:Sergio Garcia 2013.jpg|thumb|Garc\u00eda at the [[2013 BMW PGA Championship]]&thinsp;]]\nWhile tied for the lead at the [[2013 Players Championship]], Garc\u00eda hit three balls into the water on the 17th and 18th holes, finishing quadruple-bogey, double-bogey. He finished tied for eighth place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/golf/story/_/id/9268113/2013-players-championship-tiger-woods-wins-sergio-garcia-stumbles-late |title=Tiger Woods wins 4th title of year |publisher=ESPN |date=13 May 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref> After the tournament ended, Garc\u00eda and Tiger Woods (who won the tournament) had a public feud over an incident that occurred during the third round. Two weeks later, at a European Tour players dinner, Garc\u00eda was asked about meeting with Woods at the U.S. Open, to which he responded, \"We'll have him 'round every night. We will serve fried chicken.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-2329300/Sergio-Garcia-faces-losses-millions-Tiger-Woods-fried-chicken-jibe.html |title='Racist' joke costs Garcia: Spanish star could lose \u00a35m deal for fried chicken jibe at Tiger |date=22 May 2013  |newspaper=Daily Mail |first=Derek |last=Lawrenson |accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/golf/10074931/Sergio-Garcias-racist-taunt-at-world-No-1-Tiger-Woods-ahead-of-PGA-Championship-may-cost-Spaniard-millions.html |title=Sergio Garc\u00eda's racist taunt at world No 1 Tiger Woods ahead of PGA Championship may cost Spaniard millions |date=22 May 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=James |last=Corrigan |accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> The remark was seen as racist. Garc\u00eda issued a statement later that night apologizing and then issued another apology the next day, saying that his comments were \"totally stupid and out of place.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Harig |first=Bob |url=http://espn.go.com/golf/story/_/id/9300965/sergio-garcia-issues-2nd-mea-culpa-fried-chicken-remark-tiger-woods-rebuts |title=Sergio Garcia issues 2nd apology |publisher=ESPN |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/may/22/sergio-garcia-remark-tiger-woods-row |title=Sergio Garc\u00eda apologises after Tiger Woods 'fried chicken' jibe |date=22 May 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |first=Ewan |last=Murray |accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016===\nIn January 2014, Garc\u00eda won the [[Commercial Bank Qatar Masters]] after defeating [[Mikko Ilonen]] in a playoff.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/golf/25895496 |title=Sergio Garcia beats Mikko Ilonen in play-off |date=25 January 2014 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> The win put him back in the world top 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jan/25/sergio-garcia-qatar-masters |title=Sergio Garc\u00eda savours redemption after winning Qatar Masters title |date=25 January 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |first=Ewan |last=Murray |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Garc\u00eda finished joint runner-up at the [[2014 Open Championship]], two strokes behind [[Rory McIlroy]]. This was the second time Garc\u00eda had finished as a runner-up at The Open Championship and fourth time in a major championship, having still yet to break through. Garc\u00eda began the final round seven strokes behind McIlroy, but got to within two after an eagle on the 10th hole. However his challenge was ended when he left his second shot in the bunker at the par three 15th which he would bogey to fall three behind with three to play. This finish moved Garc\u00eda back inside the world's top five in the world rankings.\n\nThe biggest result of Garc\u00eda's 2015 season was at the [[2015 Players Championship]]; where he tied [[Rickie Fowler]] and [[Kevin Kisner]] at 12 under par after 72 holes. He was then eliminated after the three-hole playoff, after finishing two strokes behind Fowler and Kisner. Fowler would go on to win in sudden-death.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/golf/32685145 |title=Players Championship: Rickie Fowler wins title after superb finish |date=11 May 2015 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=17 October 2016}}</ref> On the [[Asian Tour]], he won the [[Ho Tram Open]] in [[Ph\u01b0\u1edbc Thu\u1eadn, B\u00e0 R\u1ecba-V\u0169ng T\u00e0u|Ph\u01b0\u1edbc Thu\u1eadn]], [[Vietnam]], beating [[Lin Wen-tang]], [[Himmat Rai]] and [[Thaworn Wiratchant]] in a four-way playoff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/golf/story/_/id/14301390/sergio-garcia-wins-ho-tram-open-asian-tour |title=Sergio Garcia wins Ho Tram Open on Asian Tour |date=6 December 2015 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=17 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs the year before at The Players Championship, Garc\u00eda came very close to another win on the PGA Tour at [[The Honda Classic]]. In a final round showdown with [[Adam Scott (golfer)|Adam Scott]], where the pair started the final round level, the Aussie prevailed by one shot.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-bemoans-swing-issues-after-loss |title=Sergio Garcia bemoans swing issues after loss |date=29 February 2016 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref> In May, Garc\u00eda won his second [[AT&T Byron Nelson]] championship in a playoff over [[Brooks Koepka]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-i-played-a-la-seve |title=Sergio Garcia: \"I played a la Seve\" |date=23 May 2016 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref> The win was his first on the PGA Tour since 2012 and his ninth career victory, tying [[Seve Ballesteros]] for most by a Spanish-born player.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=AT&T Byron Nelson: Garcia beats Koepka in playoff |url=http://www.golfdigest.com/story/atandt-byron-nelson-garcia-beats-koepka-in-playoff |magazine=Golf Digest |date=22 May 2016 |accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017: First major championship win===\nIn February 2017, Garc\u00eda completed a wire-to-wire victory at the [[Omega Dubai Desert Classic]] for his first European Tour title in over three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/18623803/sergio-garcia-finishes-wire-wire-victory-dubai-desert-classic |title=Sergio Garcia finishes wire-to-wire win at Dubai Desert Classic |date=5 February 2017 |publisher=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref> The victory was Garc\u00eda's 12th of his European Tour career, as he finished three strokes ahead of [[Henrik Stenson]]. The victory moved Garc\u00eda back inside the top-10 and after the win Garc\u00eda said \"Hopefully it will be the beginning of a great year.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/38872573 |title=Dubai Desert Classic: Sergio Garcia completes wire-to-wire victory |date=5 February 2017 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 Masters win====\nOn 9 April 2017, in his 74th major championship, Garc\u00eda broke through and won the [[2017 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] with victory on the first sudden-death playoff hole against [[Justin Rose]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/09/sports/golf/masters-2017-sergio-garcia-finally-wins-first-major-title.html?_r=0 |title=Masters 2017: Sergio Garc\u00eda Finally Wins First Major Title |date=9 April 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Karen |last=Crouse |accessdate=10 April 2017}}</ref> Garc\u00eda became the third Spanish player to win the Masters, after [[Seve Ballesteros]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Olaz\u00e1bal]]. The victory also came on what would have been Ballesteros' 60th birthday.\n\nGarc\u00eda shot rounds of 71-69-70 over the first three rounds to enter the final round at six-under par and in the co-lead with Rose, who played together in the final group. This represented Garc\u00eda's second career 54-hole lead/co-lead at a major championship, after the 2007 Open Championship. Garc\u00eda began the final round strongly, with two birdies on his opening three holes and he forged a three shot lead early on. Rose came back though and following bogeys on the 10th and 11th for Garc\u00eda, Rose opened up a two shot lead.\n\nThe 13th hole was then pivotal, as Garc\u00eda scrambled a par and Rose missed a short birdie putt to keep the gap at two shots. Garc\u00eda would then birdie the next hole and eagle the par five 15th to tie Rose with three holes remaining. They then both hit their tee shots at the 16th close, but only Rose converted, to again lead by one. Rose however would make a mistake at the 17th, leading to a dropped shot and meaning both players were tied going up the 72nd hole. Both players hit their approach shots close on the 18th green, but Rose burnt the lip with his birdie putt. Garc\u00eda had a five-foot putt to win the tournament in regulation play but pushed it right resulting in a playoff as both players finished level on 9-under-par after 72 holes.\n\nPlaying the 18th hole again, Rose hit his tee shot into the pine straw, meaning his second shot was blocked off by trees, so could only advance his ball 50 yards or so. He played his third to a similar area of the green he had during regulation play. Garc\u00eda fired his approach to within twelve feet. Rose's putt for par then missed on the left side of the hole, leaving Garc\u00eda with two putts for the win. He only needed one, as he holed his birdie putt for his first major championship.\n\n====Rest of 2017====\nOn 9 October 2017, it was announced that Garc\u00eda had parted ways with [[TaylorMade]] after 15 years with the equipment brand.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-announces-shock-split-from-taylormade |title=Sergio Garcia announces shock split from TaylorMade |date=9 October 2017 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks later, he won the [[Andaluc\u00eda Valderrama Masters]]. Along with the [[Omega Dubai Desert Classic]] and [[the Masters]], it was the first time he had recorded three wins in a single European Tour season. A few days after his win, he spoke about the rising tensions in Spain after the Catalan independence debate, calling on the country to 'be more together'.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-calls-for-spanish-unity |title=Sergio Garcia calls for Spanish unity |date=31 October 2017 |magazine=bunkered |first=Michael |last=McEwan}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the season-ending [[DP World Tour Championship, Dubai]] in November, Garc\u00eda dropped a huge hint that he was on the verge of signing an equipment deal with [[Callaway Golf Company]] after playing a full set of the brand's clubs in Dubai.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-talks-up-callaway-switch |title=Sergio Garcia talks up Callaway switch |date=14 November 2017 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his three-win season, Garc\u00eda was named [[European Tour Golfer of the Year]] in December.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/sergio-garcia-named-european-tour-golfer-of-the-year |title=Sergio Garcia named European Tour Golfer of the Year |date=7 December 2017 |magazine=bunkered |first=Martin |last=Inglis}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 21 January 2018, Garc\u00eda played a bogey-free 27 holes to win the [[Asian Tour]]'s [[SMBC Singapore Open]] by five strokes over [[Satoshi Kodaira]] and [[Shaun Norris (golfer)|Shaun Norris]]. Garc\u00eda shot four-under on the back nine to close out a third-round 66, then posted a closing three-under 68 in his final round.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/a-confident-sergio-garcia-wins-going-away-in-singapore/ |title=A confident Sergio Garcia wins going away in Singapore |date=21 January 2018 |magazine=Golf Digest |first=Ryan |last=Herrington |access-date=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 Masters ====\nOn 5 April 2018, in the first round of the [[2018 Masters Tournament]], Garc\u00eda tied the record for most strokes on a hole in Masters history, shooting a 13 on the 15th hole.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/05/sergio-garcia-implodes-for-a-stunning-13-on-15th-hole/ |title=Sergio Garcia implodes for a stunning 13 on 15th hole |date=5 April 2018 |newspaper=New York Post |first=Mark |last=Cannizzaro |access-date=5 April 2018}}</ref> Garc\u00eda ultimately missed the cut at the [[2018 Masters Tournament]] and failed to defend his title after shooting 81-78.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/golf/news/masters-2018-sergio-garcia-becomes-second-straight-defending-champion-to-miss-cut/ |title=Masters 2018: Sergio Garcia becomes second straight defending champion to miss cut |date=7 April 2018 |work=CBS Sports |access-date=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Rest of 2018 ====\nGarc\u00eda was a member of the [[2018 Ryder Cup]] winning European team at [[Le Golf National]] outside of Paris, France on 28\u201330 September 2018. He went 3\u20131\u20130 and won his singles match against [[Rickie Fowler]] (2 and 1). European captain [[Thomas Bj\u00f8rn]] made Garc\u00eda a captain's pick notwithstanding Garc\u00eda's inconsistent play for much of 2018, but was chosen for his passion and record in the Ryder Cup. \n\nOn 22 October 2018, Garc\u00eda successfully defended his [[Andaluc\u00eda Valderrama Masters]] hosted by the Sergio Garc\u00eda Foundation title after wrapping up a comfortable four-shot victory at [[Real Club Valderrama]] in Spain.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2018/tournamentid=2018084/news/newsid=359883.html/ |title=Brilliant Garcia successfully defends Andalucia Valerrama Masters title |date=22 October 2018 |publisher=European Tour |access-date=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn February 2019, Garc\u00eda was disqualified from the [[Saudi International (golf)|Saudi International]] tournament on the [[European Tour]] for damaging five greens deliberately in anger during his third round.<ref> {{cite web |work=Golf.com |title=Sergio Garcia DQ'd in Saudi Arabia after damaging greens 'in frustration'|url=https://www.golf.com/news/2019/02/02/sergio-garcia-disqualified-in-saudi-arabia/ |date=2 February 2019 |access-date=9 February 2019 |last=Zak |first=Sean}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Garc\u00eda was involved in another controversy at the [[WGC-Dell Technologies Match Play]]. Garc\u00eda and [[Matt Kuchar]] were locked in a quarterfinal duel when things went awry at the par-3 seventh hole. Trailing Kuchar by one, Garc\u00eda missed a seven-footer for par to win the hole, his ball coming to rest an inch or two away from the cup. Garc\u00eda went after his putt and gave it a quick-rake, and the ball lipped out. Due to the Spaniard's swiftness, Kuchar did not have a chance to concede the putt. As such, Garc\u00eda lost the hole. Kuchar told the official he wanted to give Garc\u00eda the putt, but that cannot be done retroactively. Garc\u00eda eventually lost 2 up to Kuchar, who went on to play in the finals of the event.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/golf/news/2019-wgc-match-play-sergio-garcia-wanted-matt-kuchar-to-concede-a-hole-after-botched-putt/ |work=CBS Sports |date=31 March 2019 |access-date=31 March 2019 |title=2019 WGC-Match Play: Sergio Garcia wanted Matt Kuchar to concede a hole after botched putt}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Garc\u00eda missed the cut at the Masters after shooting 73-75, which was won by [[Tiger Woods]], and the missed cut was his 6th straight in a major championship, the longest such streak in his career.\n\nIn July 2019, Garc\u00eda was again mired in controversy after throwing his driver at his caddie at the final round of the [[2019 Open Championship]] after a poor drive at the fifth hole at [[Royal Portrush Golf Club|Royal Portrush]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.golf.com/news/2019/07/24/sergio-garcia-throws-driver-caddie-open/amp/ |date=24 July 2019 |access-date=29 July 2019 |first=Kevin |last=Cunningham |work=Golf.com |title=Sergio Garcia throws driver at caddie Sunday at Portrush in resurfaced video}}</ref> Later that month, footage emerged of Garc\u00eda gouging the [[Teeing ground|teebox]] after a poor drive on the 16th hole, while competing at the [[2019 WGC-FedEx St. Jude Invitational|WGC-FedEx St. Jude Invitational]] event in Memphis.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/golf/2019/07/29/players-want-sergio-garcia-banned-latest-tantrum/ |title=Players want Sergio Garcia banned after latest tantrum |last=Corrigan |first=James |date=29 July 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph |access-date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Garc\u00eda won the [[KLM Open]] in [[Amsterdam]] with a one-shot win over teenage Danish golfer [[Nicolai H\u00f8jgaard]]. This was his sixteenth European Tour win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/golf/sergio-garcia-enjoys-a-sweet-16th-european-tour-title-with-klm-success-1.4018931 |date=15 September 2019 |access-date=16 September 2019 |work=Irish Times |title= Sergio Garcia enjoys a sweet 16th European Tour title with KLM success}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nIn January 2020, speaking ahead of the [[Abu Dhabi HSBC Championship]], Garcia revealed that he had ended his association with [[Callaway Golf Company|Callaway]] after just two years together<ref>{{cite web |url=https://golfreviewsguide.com/sergio-garcia-splits-from-callaway/ |title=Sergio Garcia Splits from Callaway |date=17 January 2020 |website=GolfReviewsGuide.com}}</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nGarc\u00eda became engaged in January 2017 to [[Golf Channel]] reporter Angela Akins, the daughter of [[Marty Akins]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/sports/2017/04/sergio-garcia-family-father-coach-victor-sister-mar-brother-mother-photos-wife-angela-ankins-spain-masters-2017/ |title=Sergio Garcia's Family: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |first=Chris |last=Bucher |date=9 April 2017 |website=heavy.com}}</ref> He is also the president and chairman of his hometown football club [[CF Borriol]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bjtonline.com/business-jet-news/sergio-garcia |title=Sergio Garcia |date=14 November 2011 |first=Matt |last=Thurber |publisher=Business Jet Traveler}}</ref> He maintains residences in [[Orlando, Florida]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/sergio-garcias-house/ |title=Sergio Garcia's House in Orlando, FL |date=17 January 2009}}</ref> [[Borriol]], and [[Crans-Montana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2015/tournamentid=2015056/news/newsid=264904.html |title=Inside Crans Montana with Sergio Garcia |publisher=PGA European Tour |date=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2018, Garc\u00eda became a father. He named his daughter Azalea, after the [[North American azaleas|famed flowers]] of [[Augusta National Golf Club]] and the nickname for the par-5 13th hole where Garc\u00eda made par to move ahead and help claim his first major.<ref>{{cite news |last=Montes |first=Silvia |title=Sergio Garc\u00eda anuncia que va a ser padre de una forma muy original |url=https://as.com/tikitakas/2017/10/12/portada/1507837362_471626.html |date=12 October 2017 |access-date=14 March 2018 |newspaper=[[Diario AS]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sergio Garc\u00eda es padre a tres semanas de Augusta |url=https://as.com/masdeporte/2018/03/14/golf/1521038076_000108.html |date=14 March 2018 |access-date=14 March 2018 |newspaper=Diario AS |language=es}}</ref>\n'''In 2020 there will be a virus called corona virus it will start in china and just go from there killing all the mostly old people and then everyone will have to stay home and all the toliet paper will be gone and everyone will freak out''' \n==Professional wins (35)==\n===PGA Tour wins (10)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n|'''Legend'''\n|- style=\"background:#e5d1cb;\"\n|Major championships  (1)\n|- style=\"background:#f2ecce;\"\n|Players Championships (1)\n|- \n|Other PGA Tour (8)\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"