{"title_page": "\u00c9ric Roy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u00c9ric Roy\n| image = \u00c9ric Roy.jpg\n| caption = Roy with [[OGC Nice|Nice]] in 2002\n| fullname = \u00c9ric Serge Roy\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1967|9|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Nice]], France\n| height = 1.88 m\n| currentclub = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (sporting director)\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1988\u20131992\n| clubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps1 = 86\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 1992\u20131993\n| clubs2 = [[Sporting Club Toulon|Toulon]]\n| caps2 = 34\n| goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1993\u20131996\n| clubs3 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]\n| caps3 = 111\n| goals3 = 9\n| years4 = 1996\u20131999\n| clubs4 = [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n| caps4 = 77\n| goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs5 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| caps5 = 27\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2001\n| clubs6 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]]\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs7 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n| caps7 = 12\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs8 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps8 = 52\n| goals8 = 2\n| totalcaps = 405\n| totalgoals = 27\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132011\n| managerclubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]] \n}}\n\n'''\u00c9ric Serge Roy''' (born 26 September 1967) is a French former professional [[association football|footballer]] and former manager of [[OGC Nice]].<ref>[http://www.rs.goal.com/en/news/90/france/2010/03/09/1824856/official-ligue-1-side-nice-sack-coach-didier-olle-nicolle Official: Ligue 1 Side Nice Sack Coach Didier Olle-Nicolle \u2013 Goal.com]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Nice]], Roy began playing professional football with [[OGC Nice]].\n\nDuring his spell in England with Sunderland, he scored once, in a 5\u20130 win over Walsall in the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportinglive.co.uk/football/premiership/sunderland/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/99/09/21/SOCCER_Walsall_Nightlead.html&TEAMHD=sunderland&DIV=prem&TEAM=SUNDERLAND&RH=Sunderland&PREV_SEASON=1998 |title=Walsall 0 Sunderland 5 (Agg: 8-2) |publisher=Sporting Life |date=21 September 1999 |accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching and management career==\n===Nice===\nAfter retiring, in September 2005 Roy was hired as director of marketing, communication and public relations at his last club [[OGC Nice]].<ref>[https://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/provence-alpes-cote-d-azur/alpes-maritimes/nice/eric-roy-quitte-l-ogc-nice-57129.html Eric Roy quitte l'OGC Nice], france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr, 15 June 2012</ref> In September 2008, he changed position to director of development and public relations. One year later, he was promoted as sporting director. In March 2010, he was appointed manager of Nice, alongside of a coach holding the professional trainer diploma, which Roy didn't. In addition to his function as sports director, Roy would receive a salary over 13 months of [[Euro|\u20ac]]17,500 in addition to bonuses.<ref name=ft>[http://www.avosports.fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=535:le-licenciement-de-lancien-directeur-sportif-de-logc-nice-etait-abusif&catid=36:actualitesjurisprudentielle&Itemid=53 Le licenciement de l'ancien directeur sportif de l'OGC Nice \u00e9tait abusif], avosports.fr, 16 June 2014</ref> He stepped down from the position in November 2011 by mutual agreement while retaining his duties as sports director.\n\n====Sacking and prosecution====\nAfter a phone call in May 2012 for a prior interview, he was officially dismissed for serious misconduct on 11 June 2012. At the end of the dismissal letter, Roy was accused of having made a 12-day trip to Argentina with an unlicensed agent despite opposition from management and without prior preparation.<ref name=ft/> Contesting the reasons for his dismissal, the employee applied to the Nice Labor Court, which by judgment in June 2013, said that the dismissal had no real and serious cause and condemned the employer for payment of the sums of \u20ac22,159 in addition to paid leave relating thereto as a reminder of salary, \u20ac97,500 in addition to paid vacation relating thereto as compensation in lieu of notice, \u20ac113,750 in severance pay, \u20ac37,573 in addition to paid vacation relating to it match and classification bonuses, \u20ac90,000 in addition to paid holidays relating thereto as maintenance bonus, \u20ac300,000 as damages for unfair dismissal, \u20ac3,000 on the basis of the provisions of article 700 of the code of civil procedure besides whole costs.<ref name=ft/>\n\nOGC Nice appealed against that judgment, arguing, first, that Roy should not have received his second remuneration as supervisor from November 2011 to the extent that it was agreed that he would give up, from this date, the daily management of the first team to occupy only its function of sports director. Nice considered, secondly, that the dismissal was perfectly regular, even in the absence of prior referral to the Legal Commission of the Professional Football League, and this insofar as its employee was not covered by the charter professional football, but the collective agreement for administrative and similar football staff (CCPAAF). Thirdly, the Club considered that the dismissal of Roy was perfectly justified in view of his insubordination and his lack of loyalty.\n\nThe case ended with Nice paying Roy nearly \u20ac300,000 for a wrongful dismissal.<ref>[https://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2013/06/18/l1-nice-condamne-a-verser-689-000-euros-a-eric-roy_3432320_3242.html L1 : Nice condamn\u00e9 \u00e0 verser 689 000 euros \u00e0 Eric Roy, son ex-entra\u00eeneur], lemonde.fr, 18 June 2013</ref>\n\n===Lens===\nOn 30 September 2017, he was appointed sporting director of [[RC Lens]].<ref>[https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/226170/article/2017-09-30/eric-roy-nomme-manager-sportif-de-lens RC LENS \u00c9ric Roy nomm\u00e9 manager sportif de Lens], lavoixdunord.fr, 30 September 2017</ref> He left the position in April 2019.<ref>[https://www.goal.com/fr/news/officiel-eric-roy-quitte-le-rc-lens/yy6l73lub9001dgdc4v3afcrv OFFICIEL - Eric Roy quitte le RC Lens], goal.com, 10 April 2019</ref>\n\n===Watford===\nIn December 2019, Roy took the role of sporting director at [[Premier League]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watfordfc.com/teams/first-team/news-sporting-director-appointment-confirmed|title=News: Sporting Director Appointment Confirmed|website=WatfordFC|language=en|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==TV==\nIn 2012, he became a consultant for the sports channel [[beIN Sports]] where he was a consultant in the program Le Club from Monday to Thursday at 7 p.m. and Friday during the pre-match and the post-match of the Ligue 1 games with Florian Genton. He left the position in 2017.<ref name=la>[https://www.lequipe.fr/Medias/Actualites/Eric-roy-nouveau-consultant-de-france-televisions/1065281 \u00c9ric Roy nouveau consultant de France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions], lequipe.fr, 2 October 2019</ref>\n\nFrom 2019, he became a consultant for [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]. He was a commentator on the matches of the [[Coupe de France]] and the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] with Kader Boudaoud (until December 2019) and later Fabien L\u00e9v\u00eaque.<ref name=la/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Leqstat|2920}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{LFP|roy-eric}}\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu}}\n\n{{OGC Nice managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Club Toulon players]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais players]]\n[[Category:Olympique de Marseille players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French football managers]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice managers]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 managers]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n\n{{France-footy-midfielder-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u00c9ric Roy\n| image = \u00c9ric Roy.jpg\n| caption = Roy with with [[OGC Nice|Nice]] in 2002\n| fullname = \u00c9ric Serge Roy\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1967|9|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Nice]], France\n| height = 1.88 m\n| currentclub = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (sporting director)\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1988\u20131992\n| clubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps1 = 86\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 1992\u20131993\n| clubs2 = [[Sporting Club Toulon|Toulon]]\n| caps2 = 34\n| goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1993\u20131996\n| clubs3 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]\n| caps3 = 111\n| goals3 = 9\n| years4 = 1996\u20131999\n| clubs4 = [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n| caps4 = 77\n| goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs5 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| caps5 = 27\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2001\n| clubs6 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]]\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs7 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n| caps7 = 12\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs8 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps8 = 52\n| goals8 = 2\n| totalcaps = 405\n| totalgoals = 27\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132011\n| managerclubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]] \n}}\n\n'''\u00c9ric Serge Roy''' (born 26 September 1967) is a French former professional [[association football|footballer]] and former manager of [[OGC Nice]].<ref>[http://www.rs.goal.com/en/news/90/france/2010/03/09/1824856/official-ligue-1-side-nice-sack-coach-didier-olle-nicolle Official: Ligue 1 Side Nice Sack Coach Didier Olle-Nicolle \u2013 Goal.com]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Nice]], Roy began playing professional football with [[OGC Nice]].\n\nDuring his spell in England with Sunderland, he scored once, in a 5\u20130 win over Walsall in the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportinglive.co.uk/football/premiership/sunderland/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/99/09/21/SOCCER_Walsall_Nightlead.html&TEAMHD=sunderland&DIV=prem&TEAM=SUNDERLAND&RH=Sunderland&PREV_SEASON=1998 |title=Walsall 0 Sunderland 5 (Agg: 8-2) |publisher=Sporting Life |date=21 September 1999 |accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching and management career==\n===Nice===\nAfter retiring, in September 2005 Roy was hired as director of marketing, communication and public relations at his last club [[OGC Nice]].<ref>[https://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/provence-alpes-cote-d-azur/alpes-maritimes/nice/eric-roy-quitte-l-ogc-nice-57129.html Eric Roy quitte l'OGC Nice], france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr, 15 June 2012</ref> In September 2008, he changed position to director of development and public relations. One year later, he was promoted as sporting director. In March 2010, he was appointed manager of Nice, alongside of a coach holding the professional trainer diploma, which Roy didn't. In addition to his function as sports director, Roy would receive a salary over 13 months of [[Euro|\u20ac]]17,500 in addition to bonuses.<ref name=ft>[http://www.avosports.fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=535:le-licenciement-de-lancien-directeur-sportif-de-logc-nice-etait-abusif&catid=36:actualitesjurisprudentielle&Itemid=53 Le licenciement de l'ancien directeur sportif de l'OGC Nice \u00e9tait abusif], avosports.fr, 16 June 2014</ref> He stepped down from the position in November 2011 by mutual agreement while retaining his duties as sports director.\n\n====Sacking and prosecution====\nAfter a phone call in May 2012 for a prior interview, he was officially dismissed for serious misconduct on 11 June 2012. At the end of the dismissal letter, Roy was accused of having made a 12-day trip to Argentina with an unlicensed agent despite opposition from management and without prior preparation.<ref name=ft/> Contesting the reasons for his dismissal, the employee applied to the Nice Labor Court, which by judgment in June 2013, said that the dismissal had no real and serious cause and condemned the employer for payment of the sums of \u20ac22,159 in addition to paid leave relating thereto as a reminder of salary, \u20ac97,500 in addition to paid vacation relating thereto as compensation in lieu of notice, \u20ac113,750 in severance pay, \u20ac37,573 in addition to paid vacation relating to it match and classification bonuses, \u20ac90,000 in addition to paid holidays relating thereto as maintenance bonus, \u20ac300,000 as damages for unfair dismissal, \u20ac3,000 on the basis of the provisions of article 700 of the code of civil procedure besides whole costs.<ref name=ft/>\n\nOGC Nice appealed against that judgment, arguing, first, that Roy should not have received his second remuneration as supervisor from November 2011 to the extent that it was agreed that he would give up, from this date, the daily management of the first team to occupy only its function of sports director. Nice considered, secondly, that the dismissal was perfectly regular, even in the absence of prior referral to the Legal Commission of the Professional Football League, and this insofar as its employee was not covered by the charter professional football, but the collective agreement for administrative and similar football staff (CCPAAF). Thirdly, the Club considered that the dismissal of Roy was perfectly justified in view of his insubordination and his lack of loyalty.\n\nThe case ended with Nice paying Roy nearly \u20ac300,000 for a wrongful dismissal.<ref>[https://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2013/06/18/l1-nice-condamne-a-verser-689-000-euros-a-eric-roy_3432320_3242.html L1 : Nice condamn\u00e9 \u00e0 verser 689 000 euros \u00e0 Eric Roy, son ex-entra\u00eeneur], lemonde.fr, 18 June 2013</ref>\n\n===Lens===\nOn 30 September 2017, he was appointed sporting director of [[RC Lens]].<ref>[https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/226170/article/2017-09-30/eric-roy-nomme-manager-sportif-de-lens RC LENS \u00c9ric Roy nomm\u00e9 manager sportif de Lens], lavoixdunord.fr, 30 September 2017</ref> He left the position in April 2019.<ref>[https://www.goal.com/fr/news/officiel-eric-roy-quitte-le-rc-lens/yy6l73lub9001dgdc4v3afcrv OFFICIEL - Eric Roy quitte le RC Lens], goal.com, 10 April 2019</ref>\n\n===Watford===\nIn December 2019, Roy took the role of sporting director at [[Premier League]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watfordfc.com/teams/first-team/news-sporting-director-appointment-confirmed|title=News: Sporting Director Appointment Confirmed|website=WatfordFC|language=en|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==TV==\nIn 2012, he became a consultant for the sports channel [[beIN Sports]] where he was a consultant in the program Le Club from Monday to Thursday at 7 p.m. and Friday during the pre-match and the post-match of the Ligue 1 games with Florian Genton. He left the position in 2017.<ref name=la>[https://www.lequipe.fr/Medias/Actualites/Eric-roy-nouveau-consultant-de-france-televisions/1065281 \u00c9ric Roy nouveau consultant de France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions], lequipe.fr, 2 October 2019</ref>\n\nFrom 2019, he became a consultant for [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]. He was a commentator on the matches of the [[Coupe de France]] and the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] with Kader Boudaoud (until December 2019) and later Fabien L\u00e9v\u00eaque.<ref name=la/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Leqstat|2920}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{LFP|roy-eric}}\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu}}\n\n{{OGC Nice managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Club Toulon players]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais players]]\n[[Category:Olympique de Marseille players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French football managers]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice managers]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 managers]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n\n{{France-footy-midfielder-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89ric_Roy"}
{"title_page": "Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Pilot\n| series         = How to Get Away with Murder\n| image          = <!-- bare filename only. Wikilinking, \"File:\", and pixel size not required. -->\n| image_size     = <!-- raw number. \"px\" not required. -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 1\n| episode        = 9\n| director       = [[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]]\n| writer         = Michael Foley & Erika Green Swafford\n| producer       = \n| music          = \n| photographer   = \n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{start date|2014|11|20}}\n| length         = 43 minutes\n| guests         = \n*[[Tom Verica]] - Sam Keating\n*[[Lynn Whitfield]] - Mary Walker\n*[[Pat Healy (actor)|Pat Healy]] - Dennis\n*[[Conrad Ricamora]] - Oliver Hampton\n| prev           = He Has a Wife\n| next           = Hello Raskolnikov\n| season_article = How to Get Away with Murder (season 1)\n| episode_list   = List of How to Get Away with Murder episodes\n}}\n\"'''Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me'''\" is the ninth episode of the [[How to Get Away with Murder (season 1)|first season]] of the American [[legal drama]] television series ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''. The [[List of How to Get Away with Murder episodes|ninth episode]] overall and [[midseason finale]], it was written by Michael Foley and Erika Green Swafford, and directed by [[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]]. It was first aired on November 20, 2014 on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], following ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'s'' [[Grey's Anatomy (season 11)|eleventh season]] and ''[[Scandal]]'s'' [[Scandal (season 4)|fourth season]] on the network's [[TGIT]] programming.\n\n__TOC__\n== Plot ==\nThe night of the bonfire catches up with the present timeline during this episode, with all the flashforwards piecing out the night that led the Keating 4 to end up killing Sam Keating.\n\nHaving just discovered that Lila was pregnant with her husband's baby, Annalise packs Sam's belongings and tries to kick him out of their house. On a long and intense argument, Annalise accuses Sam of killing Lila and provokes him to do the same to herself \u2013hence the episode title\u2013 and she leaves the house in anger to find comfort on [[List of How to Get Away with Murder characters#Nate Lahey|Nate]].\n\nOn the midst of the Bonfire night celebration, Wes, Connor, and Laurel hurry to the Keating's household to stop Rebecca from hurting her own case. Wes finds out that Rebecca spoke with Nate, and he adviced her to steal phone information from Sam's laptop in an attempt to prove he killed Lila. Wes confesses to the others that he and Rebecca believe Sam killed Lila and had been hiding this knowledge from the group all along.\n\nMichaela, having stolen the trophy from Asher, visits Annalise's house to turn the trophy in and get herself excused from the upcoming exam. Inside, Michaela encounters Sam, who tries to get her to leave, but she insists on staying to give Annalise the trophy. Michaela notices Rebecca breaking in and calls Sam's attention to her, but Sam, thinking the two are involved a joint scheme, becomes hostile. Rebecca tells Michaela to call Wes before running upstairs to Sam's room. Rebecca locks herself in and begins uploading the data evidence from Sam's computer onto Nate's flash drive while Sam shouts and bangs on the door. At the same time, Michaela contacts Wes and explains the situation, begging him and the others to defuse the conflict.\n\nWes and company arrive at Annalise's house just as Rebecca has finished transferring all the evidence onto Nate's flash drive. Rebecca returns Sam's laptop to him and claims having found nothing with which to incriminate him. Sam, knowing this to be a lie, tackles Rebecca and a scuffle for the flash drive ensues. Rebecca passes the drive to Laurel who then flees the room. Sam attempts to chase her but he is shoved by Michaela and accidentally thrown over the stairs. Sam falls down two stories face-first and is motionless; the Keating 4 think he's dead.\n\nAs they all panic and start discussing their options, Sam starts silently choking Rebecca on the living room. Once Wes realizes that, he takes the trophy and hits Sam on the back of his head with it, instantly killing him. Still on shock, Wes cleans up Rebecca upstairs; Laurel cleans the trophy; and both Michaela and Connor freak out on the house about what just happened. Wes tells his friends he's gonna take Rebecca somewhere safe, and asks them to meet him at the woods in an hour.\n\nIn the meantime, after being fired by Annalise, Bonnie almost sleeps with a man on a hotel, but she ends up backing up at the last minute. She decides to call Asher instead, since they will not be working together anymore. Asher celebrates and prepares for spending time with Bonnie.\n\nAs seen on previous flashforwards, the Keating 4 decide to flip a coin and they end up going back into the house to take the body with them. They go on the Middleton woods and are almost caught a couple of times. Wes, Connor and Michaela notice that Frank called Laurel, which results on her telling them that she cheated on her boyfriend with Frank, but she also asks them to judge her while they carry the body through the woods.\n\nLater that night, the group burns Sam's body and then bag his remains for destruction at an incinerator. Michaela loses her engagement ring and attempts to find it in the ashes but is forced by the group to relinquish her search. With Michaela emotionally unable to return the Justice trophy and thus an alibi for the murder weapon, Laurel volunteers herself for the task. Losing control of the situation, Wes cannot convince the group to move forward with the incineration and the party discards Sam's bagged remains into a public dumpster. The group parts ways.\n\nMeanwhile, Annalise confides in Nate her suspicion that Sam murdered Lila and regrets her past efforts to protect Sam's reputation and their marriage. She apologizes for having gotten Nate fired and confesses her feelings for him. Annalise and Nate make love, overwhelmed by the weight of their failing marriages. Asher and Bonnie also have sex on his house, and Bonnie later receives a call from Annalise, telling her that something bad happened and Sam's gone missing.\n\nConnor, on the verge of a nervous breakdown, visits Oliver and spends the night with him. In the morning, he tells Oliver that he has a drug addiction, and that's the reason he had a nervous breakdown last night. Michaela signs a pre-nup deal with her mother-in-law, wearing gloves to prevent her from noticing her ring's missing. Laurel gives Frank the trophy, and asks him to return him, saying that she stole it and she now regrets it. Wes, on the other hand, spends the night with Rebecca on a motel. All of the students get a text message from Annalise that same morning, asking them to come by her house. Once they're all in there, she tells them Sam is missing, and asks them to cooperate with the police investigating into his disappearance since he is now a suspect on Lila Stangard's murder. \n\nIn the final minutes of the episode, a flashback shows that Wes came back to the Keating Household before meeting with his classmates. While looking at Sam's dead body, he says \"I'm so sorry\", but a voice in the background surprises him: Annalise, telling him: \"Don't be\". It is then implied that Wes explained everything to Annalise, and she guided him through the night after they accidentally killed the professor's husband.\n\n== Featured Music ==\n*\"Walk with the Noise\" - [[IAMX]]\n*\"Black Out Days\" - [[Phantogram]]\n*\"Vision\" - [[M83 (band)|M83]]\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Viewers ===\nIn its original American broadcast, the How to Get Away with Murder's \"Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me\" was seen by an estimated 9.82 million household viewers and gained a 3.1/10 ratings share among adults aged 18\u201349, according to Nielsen Media Research. <ref name=\"1.09\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/11/21/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-adjusted-up-gracepoint-reign-parenthood-bad-judge-mom-two-and-a-half-men-the-biggest-loser-a-to-z-adjusted-down/330218/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory' Adjusted Up; 'Gracepoint', 'Reign', 'Parenthood', 'Bad Judge', 'Mom', 'Two and a Half Men' 'The Biggest Loser' & 'A to Z' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 21, 2014|accessdate=November 21, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123164454/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/11/21/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-adjusted-up-gracepoint-reign-parenthood-bad-judge-mom-two-and-a-half-men-the-biggest-loser-a-to-z-adjusted-down/330218/|archivedate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> This means that 3.1 percent of all households with televisions watched the episode, while 10 percent of all households watching television at that time watched it. The episode also attached 4.93 million DVR viewers, summing up 14.76 million viewers. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/12/08/modern-family-has-biggest-adults-18-49-ratings-increase-reign-tops-percentage-gains-the-big-bang-theory-leads-viewer-gains-in-live-7-ratings-for-week-8-ending-november-16/336692/|title='Modern Family' Has Biggest Adults 18-49 Ratings Increase; 'Reign' Tops Percentage Gains & 'The Big Bang Theory' Leads Viewer Gains in Live +7 Ratings for Week 8 Ending November 16|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Bibel|accessdate=December 8, 2014|date=December 8, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218065004/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/12/08/modern-family-has-biggest-adults-18-49-ratings-increase-reign-tops-percentage-gains-the-big-bang-theory-leads-viewer-gains-in-live-7-ratings-for-week-8-ending-november-16/336692/|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical Response ===\nOn the midseason finale, Marc Snetiker from [[Entertainment Weekly]] had to say: \"Truthfully, my hat is off to Pete Nowalk and Shonda Rhimes for delivering what can only be deemed a real, genuine pay-off. And now I can\u2019t wait to come back on January 29 for the next batch!\". <ref name=\"EW review\">{{cite web |last1=Snetiker |first1=Marc |title=How to Get Away with Murder recap: 'Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me' |url=https://ew.com/recap/how-to-get-away-with-murder-season-1-episode-9/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first [[midseason finale]] has a grade of 83% from over 6 critics, meaning certified fresh as per the website standards. <ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes episode\">{{cite web |title=How to Get Away with Murder > Season 1 > Episode 9 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/how_to_get_away_with_murder/s01/e09 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{How to Get Away with Murder}}\n\n[[Category:2014 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:How to Get Away with Murder]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Pilot\n| series         = How to Get Away with Murder\n| image          = <!-- bare filename only. Wikilinking, \"File:\", and pixel size not required. -->\n| image_size     = <!-- raw number. \"px\" not required. -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 1\n| episode        = 9\n| director       = [[Stephen Williams]]\n| writer         = Michael Foley & Erika Green Swafford\n| producer       = \n| music          = \n| photographer   = \n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{start date|2014|11|20}}\n| length         = 43 minutes\n| guests         = \n*[[Tom Verica]] - Sam Keating\n*[[Lynn Whitfield]] - Mary Walker\n*[[Pat Healy]] - Dennis\n*[[Conrad Ricamora]] - Oliver Hampton\n| prev           = He Has a Wife\n| next           = Hello Raskolnikov\n| season_article = How to Get Away with Murder (season 1)\n| episode_list   = List of How to Get Away with Murder episodes\n}}\n\"'''Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me'''\" is the ninth episode of the [[How to Get Away with Murder (season 1)|first season]] of the American [[legal drama]] television series ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''. The [[List of How to Get Away with Murder episodes|ninth episode]] overall and [[midseason finale]], it was written by Michael Foley and Erika Green Swafford, and directed by [[Stephen Williams]]. It was first aired on November 20, 2014 on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], following ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'s'' [[Grey's Anatomy (season 11)|eleventh season]] and ''[[Scandal]]'s'' [[Scandal (season 4)|fourth season]] on the network's [[TGIT]] programming.\n\n__TOC__\n== Plot ==\nThe night of the bonfire catches up with the present timeline during this episode, with all the flashforwards piecing out the night that led the Keating 4 to end up killing Sam Keating.\n\nHaving just discovered that Lila was pregnant with her husband's baby, Annalise packs Sam's belongings and tries to kick him out of their house. On a long and intense argument, Annalise accuses Sam of killing Lila and provokes him to do the same to herself \u2013hence the episode title\u2013 and she leaves the house in anger to find comfort on [[List of How to Get Away with Murder characters#Nate Lahey|Nate]].\n\nOn the midst of the Bonfire night celebration, Wes, Connor, and Laurel hurry to the Keating's household to stop Rebecca from hurting her own case. Wes finds out that Rebecca spoke with Nate, and he adviced her to steal phone information from Sam's laptop in an attempt to prove he killed Lila. Wes confesses to the others that he and Rebecca believe Sam killed Lila and had been hiding this knowledge from the group all along.\n\nMichaela, having stolen the trophy from Asher, visits Annalise's house to turn the trophy in and get herself excused from the upcoming exam. Inside, Michaela encounters Sam, who tries to get her to leave, but she insists on staying to give Annalise the trophy. Michaela notices Rebecca breaking in and calls Sam's attention to her, but Sam, thinking the two are involved a joint scheme, becomes hostile. Rebecca tells Michaela to call Wes before running upstairs to Sam's room. Rebecca locks herself in and begins uploading the data evidence from Sam's computer onto Nate's flash drive while Sam shouts and bangs on the door. At the same time, Michaela contacts Wes and explains the situation, begging him and the others to defuse the conflict.\n\nWes and company arrive at Annalise's house just as Rebecca has finished transferring all the evidence onto Nate's flash drive. Rebecca returns Sam's laptop to him and claims having found nothing with which to incriminate him. Sam, knowing this to be a lie, tackles Rebecca and a scuffle for the flash drive ensues. Rebecca passes the drive to Laurel who then flees the room. Sam attempts to chase her but he is shoved by Michaela and accidentally thrown over the stairs. Sam falls down two stories face-first and is motionless; the Keating 4 think he's dead.\n\nAs they all panic and start discussing their options, Sam starts silently choking Rebecca on the living room. Once Wes realizes that, he takes the trophy and hits Sam on the back of his head with it, instantly killing him. Still on shock, Wes cleans up Rebecca upstairs; Laurel cleans the trophy; and both Michaela and Connor freak out on the house about what just happened. Wes tells his friends he's gonna take Rebecca somewhere safe, and asks them to meet him at the woods in an hour.\n\nIn the meantime, after being fired by Annalise, Bonnie almost sleeps with a man on a hotel, but she ends up backing up at the last minute. She decides to call Asher instead, since they will not be working together anymore. Asher celebrates and prepares for spending time with Bonnie.\n\nAs seen on previous flashforwards, the Keating 4 decide to flip a coin and they end up going back into the house to take the body with them. They go on the Middleton woods and are almost caught a couple of times. Wes, Connor and Michaela notice that Frank called Laurel, which results on her telling them that she cheated on her boyfriend with Frank, but she also asks them to judge her while they carry the body through the woods.\n\nLater that night, the group burns Sam's body and then bag his remains for destruction at an incinerator. Michaela loses her engagement ring and attempts to find it in the ashes but is forced by the group to relinquish her search. With Michaela emotionally unable to return the Justice trophy and thus an alibi for the murder weapon, Laurel volunteers herself for the task. Losing control of the situation, Wes cannot convince the group to move forward with the incineration and the party discards Sam's bagged remains into a public dumpster. The group parts ways.\n\nMeanwhile, Annalise confides in Nate her suspicion that Sam murdered Lila and regrets her past efforts to protect Sam's reputation and their marriage. She apologizes for having gotten Nate fired and confesses her feelings for him. Annalise and Nate make love, overwhelmed by the weight of their failing marriages. Asher and Bonnie also have sex on his house, and Bonnie later receives a call from Annalise, telling her that something bad happened and Sam's gone missing.\n\nConnor, on the verge of a nervous breakdown, visits Oliver and spends the night with him. In the morning, he tells Oliver that he has a drug addiction, and that's the reason he had a nervous breakdown last night. Michaela signs a pre-nup deal with her mother-in-law, wearing gloves to prevent her from noticing her ring's missing. Laurel gives Frank the trophy, and asks him to return him, saying that she stole it and she now regrets it. Wes, on the other hand, spends the night with Rebecca on a motel. All of the students get a text message from Annalise that same morning, asking them to come by her house. Once they're all in there, she tells them Sam is missing, and asks them to cooperate with the police investigating into his disappearance since he is now a suspect on Lila Stangard's murder. \n\nIn the final minutes of the episode, a flashback shows that Wes came back to the Keating Household before meeting with his classmates. While looking at Sam's dead body, he says \"I'm so sorry\", but a voice in the background surprises him: Annalise, telling him: \"Don't be\". It is then implied that Wes explained everything to Annalise, and she guided him through the night after they accidentally killed the professor's husband.\n\n== Featured Music ==\n*\"Walk with the Noise\" - [[IAMX]]\n*\"Black Out Days\" - [[Phantogram]]\n*\"Vision\" - [[M83]]\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Viewers ===\nIn its original American broadcast, the How to Get Away with Murder's \"Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me\" was seen by an estimated 9.82 million household viewers and gained a 3.1/10 ratings share among adults aged 18\u201349, according to Nielsen Media Research. <ref name=\"1.09\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/11/21/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-adjusted-up-gracepoint-reign-parenthood-bad-judge-mom-two-and-a-half-men-the-biggest-loser-a-to-z-adjusted-down/330218/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory' Adjusted Up; 'Gracepoint', 'Reign', 'Parenthood', 'Bad Judge', 'Mom', 'Two and a Half Men' 'The Biggest Loser' & 'A to Z' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 21, 2014|accessdate=November 21, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123164454/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/11/21/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-adjusted-up-gracepoint-reign-parenthood-bad-judge-mom-two-and-a-half-men-the-biggest-loser-a-to-z-adjusted-down/330218/|archivedate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> This means that 3.1 percent of all households with televisions watched the episode, while 10 percent of all households watching television at that time watched it. The episode also attached 4.93 million DVR viewers, summing up 14.76 million viewers. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/12/08/modern-family-has-biggest-adults-18-49-ratings-increase-reign-tops-percentage-gains-the-big-bang-theory-leads-viewer-gains-in-live-7-ratings-for-week-8-ending-november-16/336692/|title='Modern Family' Has Biggest Adults 18-49 Ratings Increase; 'Reign' Tops Percentage Gains & 'The Big Bang Theory' Leads Viewer Gains in Live +7 Ratings for Week 8 Ending November 16|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Bibel|accessdate=December 8, 2014|date=December 8, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218065004/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/12/08/modern-family-has-biggest-adults-18-49-ratings-increase-reign-tops-percentage-gains-the-big-bang-theory-leads-viewer-gains-in-live-7-ratings-for-week-8-ending-november-16/336692/|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical Response ===\nOn the midseason finale, Marc Snetiker from [[Entertainment Weekly]] had to say: \"Truthfully, my hat is off to Pete Nowalk and Shonda Rhimes for delivering what can only be deemed a real, genuine pay-off. And now I can\u2019t wait to come back on January 29 for the next batch!\". <ref name=\"EW review\">{{cite web |last1=Snetiker |first1=Marc |title=How to Get Away with Murder recap: 'Kill Me, Kill Me, Kill Me' |url=https://ew.com/recap/how-to-get-away-with-murder-season-1-episode-9/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first [[midseason finale]] has a grade of 83% from over 6 critics, meaning certified fresh as per the website standards. <ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes episode\">{{cite web |title=How to Get Away with Murder > Season 1 > Episode 9 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/how_to_get_away_with_murder/s01/e09 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=21 April 2020}}